english:
  title: On the National Academy
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servants humbly submit this memorial:

    We have witnessed how the sage upon the throne, on the fifteenth day of this month, graced the National Academy with his presence. There he made offerings to the Most Sage and文宣 King, and commanded the Grand Rector Park Seung-joong to expound upon the three chapters of the Canon's "Counsels of Yu." The imperial carriage and banners of jade cast their light upon the halls of learning, while officials in ceremonial robes gathered at the bridge gate. Joy descended upon the realm, and virtue spread across the ten thousand lands.

    We reflect upon this truth: the study of the Classics illuminates the Way, yet without worthy men it bears no fruit. The Academy cultivates talent, yet it awaits its proper season to flourish. That the great ceremonies are now performed speaks well of this luminous age.

    How reverent we are of the Sage upon the throne! His Way reaches the heights of clarity; his governance flows from benevolence and righteousness. He mirrors the ancient wisdom of Yao and Shun, embodies the literary refinement of Yin and Zhou. Following the old patterns, he has established these noble rites—bowing before the Sage and offering the cup, commanding the learned to expound the Classics. The gentlemen he cultivates shall surely sing the songs of growth and flourishing; the warriors who present their honors shall certainly achieve the glory of the hall of learning. This is no mere celebration of a single moment, but glory that shall endure through ten thousand generations.

    We, your humble servants, are fortunate to live in this enlightened age, unworthy as we are to hold office. We gaze upon virtue from our lowly station, receiving the radiance of the Sage's learning. Like those who stand at the shore in autumn, gazing upon the vast sea, we cannot measure the depth of our wonder. Yet like new shoots of spring touched by the royal hand, we know ourselves blessed.
  footnotes:
    - The memorial uses the formal bureaucratic register, characteristic of official court documents of the Koryŏ period.
    - References to Yao and Shun invoke the sage-kings of Chinese antiquity; Yin and Zhou refer to ancient Chinese dynasties known for their cultural refinement.
    - The final metaphors of the autumn shore and spring shoots, drawn from classical sources, express the subjects' sense of both the infinite distance between themselves and the sovereign's wisdom, and their gratitude for being illuminated by it.
